Recap from Last week

 

Last week I introduced you to visualization in R and Gephi. We can learn quite a lot from visualization. Everything from identifying patterns of missing data to three and four-way interactions between variables. But in the end, many of you will also want to run more complex analysis

Statistical Analaysis is R

 

R is probably the most sophisticated tool for statistical analyses currently available- if only because it is the most widely used software by statisticians who produce many of the models we want to use. Also, R's Open Source structure means that the latest and greatest statistical techniques will be available in R long before they are built into SAS/STATA/SPSS etc.

A Very Brief Introduction

 

In this class, we will learn how to perform very basic statistics in R. We could easily spend an entire semester studying the latest and greatest linear models in R. Instead my goal- as always- is to teach you just enough that you could learn more on your own if you so choose.

Big Data, Big Problems

 

One of the themes of today's class will be that big data/ computational social science datasets present some new challenges for linear models. We will talk about these and next week we will discuss some of the exciting alternatives that are coming online.

Pew Data on Support for "Ground-Zero Mosque"

 

load("Pew Data.Rdata")

Who Supports/Opposes?

 

Let's try to predict whether people support or oppose the ground zero mosque (this variable is labelled pew10) 1=oppose construction, 2= support construction

table(pewdata$pew10)

Code them Republicans!

 

Use the partlyn variable to examine whether party identification predicts opposition

pewdata$Republican<-0
pewdata$Republican[pewdata$partlyn=="Republican"]<-1

Correlations

We know the relationships is significantly different, but was is the direction? To figure this out we need to run a correlation. We can use the cor.test command

cor.test(pewdata$pew10, pewdata$Republican)

Behold, the Correlogram

 

One of the most useful things about R is that it can very easily and efficiently combine statistics and visualization.

Behold, the Correlogram

 

Let's say we wanted to quickly identify variables with significant correlations with each other. The corrgram package produces a “heatmap-style” correlation matrix:

install.packages("corrgram")
library(corrgram)
corrgram(pewdata)

Behold... the Correlogram

What about Age?

 

but what if we are concerned that age is a confounding factor in this relationship. That is, older people might be less accepting of Muslims regardless of party identification.

Good ol' OLS

 

To figure this out, we'd need to run a multiple linear regression model. In R, the syntax for this is:

lm(pew10~Republican+age, pewdata)


Call:
lm(formula = pew10 ~ Republican + age, data = pewdata)

Coefficients:
(Intercept)   Republican          age  
   1.659028           NA    -0.005331

Good ol' OLS

 

Instead of:

lm(pew10~Republican+age, pewdata)

We could also write:

lm(pewdata$pew10~pewdata$Republican+pewdata$age)

Good ol' OLS

 

But the code we just ran doesn't give us the output we want. This is because R stores the output as an object. so we need to write something like:

results<-lm(pew10~Republican+age, pewdata)

Good ol' OLS

 

To see the regression results, we need to write:

summary(results)

For example, if we want to get the coefficiences, we can use the $ operator to get the coefficients

results$coefficients

Good ol' OLS

 

we can also plot the residuals values easily:

plot(results)

(You need to hit return to see the different types of plots available).

Behold... the scatterplot matrix

The “pairs” command lets us look at scatterplots for every pair of variables in the dataset. Lets use the mtcars data because it has a lot of continuous variables that illustrate the power of this technique nicely

pairs(~ mpg + hp + cyl, data=mtcars)

Diagnostic Tests

 

R also includes every single diagnostic test available. For exmaple, here is the command for evaluating MultiCollinearity/Variance Inflation Factors:

library(car)
vif(results)

...And More Diagnostic Tests

 

Here is the Bonferonni p-value for the most extreme observations:

outlierTest(results)

comes up negative.

...And More Diagnostic Tests

 

Some of the tools are even interactive:

influencePlot(results,  id.method="identify", main="Influence Plot", sub="Circle size is proportial to Cook's Distance" )

...And More Diagnostic Tests

 

There are also popular tools for assessing non-normality:

qqPlot(results)

It looks a little funky because it is bimodal. Normally we use a qqplot to asses wether the data fit a normal distribution.

You might also like:

leveragePlots(results)
av.Plots(results)

...But wait... there's more!

 

We can also evaluate homoscedasticity using a non-constant error variance test:

ncvTest(results)

...Make the Diagnostic Tests Stop, Please

 

look for non-linearity:

crPlots(results)

looks ok.

...What about Missing Data?

The VIM package is like a magical fairy that rides on a unicorn… seriously:

install.packages("VIM")
library(VIM)
aggr(pewdata)

...What about Missing Data?

VIM also has a variety of functions that let you identify extremely complex patterns in missing data, for example the marginmatrix command is a mashup of the matrix scatterplot and the missing data visualizations we just saw. I'm going to run it on a subset of the data:

subsample<-pewdata[,c("age","sex","pew10")]
marginmatrix(subsample)

"Figure margins too large?"

 

If you get this error, try making the “plot” window bigger in RStudio.

Much to Do About Missing Data

 

Looks like we have a lot of missing data, what should we do about it? After carefully inspecting the patterns of missing data, we could consider multiple imputation. Keep in mind, however, that you should only run MI after carefully specifying your model, and completing any variable transformations that are necessary.

Much to Do About Missing Data

 

Here's how to perform multiple imputation using chained equations in r:

library(mice)
mice.dat <- mice(subsample,m=10,seed=3)
mice.dat <- complete(mice.dat,action=10)

Next, we would rerun our model using mice.dat

Now You Try It:

 

Determine whether the relationship between mpg and hp of a car is significant when controlling for the number of cylinders, quarter second time (qsec), and whether or not a car is automatic (using the “am” variable)“

FIXED-EFFECTS

Fixed Effects

 

This is how to run a fixed-effects model

fixed<-(lm(pew10~Republican+age+factor(state), data=pewdata))

RANDOM EFFECTS

Random Effects

 

This is how to run a random effects model

install.packages("lme4")
library(lme4)
random<-lmer(pew10~Republican+age+ (1|state), data=pewdata)

Random Effects

 

To specify a different distribution of the outcome, use the “family” argument:

random<-lmer(pew10~Republican+age+ (1|state), family=poisson, data=pewdata)

We get some funky error messages here because we chose a family that do not fit the data.

Fixed or Random?

 

To determine whether or not to use random effects we can use the Breusch-Pagan test- if it is significant this suggests the random model is better way to describe the data.

install.packages("lmtest")
library(lmtest)
bptest(fixed, random)

this suggests we should use the random effects model.

Time-Series

These “conditioning plots”“ help us see if the relationships between sectors really vary across year:

coplot(wage ~ year|firm, type="l", data=EmplUK)

Time-Series

I also like to plot the means across time:

install.packages("gplots")
library(gplots)
plotmeans(wage ~ year, main="Heterogeineity across time", data=EmplUK)

Time-Series

It's also useful to look at means across the firms:

plotmeans(wage ~ firm, main="Heterogeineity across Firms", data=EmplUK)

Time-Series

**we are seeing clear differences across both time and firms so we will probably want to look at both fixed and random effects panel models. First, let's run fixed effects:

library(plm)
fixed1 <- plm(wage ~ capital+output+emp, index=c("firm", "year"), data=EmplUK, model="within")
summary(fixed1)

Diagnostics

Here is the test for serial correlation:

library(lmtest)
pbgtest(random1)

We should also test for cross-sectional dependence/contemporaneous causation:

pcdtest(random1, test = c("lm"))

And of course, we could test for much, much more…

Large datasets collected in computational social science often involve many vari ables- so many that it can be difficult to know where to begin to analyze the many relationships between them, and how they relate to an outcome. Random forests are an interesting new tool that can be used to capture causal complexity, and begin to get a better sense of your data. We will need to discuss, however, whether and how they might become part of the computational sociologists per- manent toolkit.
